<p>On March 19, 1830, Nelly Lemon, through her attorneys Coxe and Smith, <!--petitioned for her and her children's freedom--><%= link_to "petitioned for her and her children's freedom", case_path("oscys.caseid.0190") %>. The language of the <!--petition--><%= link_to "petition", doc_path("oscys.case.0188.001") %> includes very little beyond a statement of her claim to freedom. The <!--summons--><%= link_to "summons", doc_path("oscys.case.0188.003") %> was issued that same day, but per the endorsement on the back, the marshal did not successfully summon John Bayne, Lemon's putative owner<!--, reporting his failure in August of that year,-->. A <!--second summons--><%= link_to "second summons", doc_path("oscys.case.0188.004") %> was issued that August, but this too failed. The case ground to a halt until 1832 when Lemon tried again, filing <!--another petition--><%= link_to "another petition", doc_path("oscys.case.0188.002") %> with new attorneys. A <!--new summons--><%= link_to "new summons", doc_path("oscys.case.0188.005") %> was issued the same day, and Bayne proved slippery again, failing to be found by the end of May. However, as is typical with court records, the surviving documentation doesn't tell the whole story. Bayne was apparently successfully summoned and the case tried during the June 1832 sessions of the court. This kind of lacuna is instructive&#8212;reading a case file chronologically will often result in gaps where a researcher is left to her imagination and inference to fill in the details.</p> 

<h3>Pre-Trial Documents</h3>

<p>For some cases though, the <em>OSCYS</em> database includes pre-trial material such as <!--depositions, affidavits, certificates,--><%= link_to "depositions", search_path({:qfield => "subCategory", :qtext => "Deposition"}) %>, <%= link_to "affidavits", search_path({:qfield => "subCategory", :qtext => "Affidavit"}) %>, <%= link_to "certificates", search_path({:qfield => "subCategory", :qtext => "Certificate"}) %> and other supporting documentation. Depositions were official statements of fact solicited by attorneys in a case, sworn to by a witness, and submitted to the court. Similarly, affidavits were also sworn statements volunteered by members of the community or even the parties to the case themselves in hopes of securing a point of fact. Finally, <!--interrogatories--><%= link_to "interrogatories", search_path({:qfield => "subCategory", :qtext => "Interrogatories"}) %> were lists of questions submitted by attorneys to be answered by witnesses relating to the facts at hand. Where they exist, interrogatories can prove to be the most detail-rich of any court document. Full of highly specific questions related to the background of the enslaved person and his/her claim to freedom, they frequently offer quotidian details about domestic life, conditions of enslavement, and family dynamics. These lists of questions, of course, were engineered by lawyers and the witnesses only answered what was asked of them&#8212;and not often wholly truthfully at that. Leading questions litter the documents in an attempt to spin the narrative one direction or another, such as <!--this question--><%= link_to "this question", doc_path("oscys.case.0083.006") %> on behalf of a slave owner: "Do you or do you not know that after the said sale and purchase the petitioner broke jail in the town of Alexandria and was a runaway for a considerable length of time thereafter."</p>

